## Core mental model (always true)

- **Starters + auto-configuration.** A starter (`spring-boot-starter-*`) is a dependency aggregator
  that pulls a coherent set of libraries onto the classpath. `@EnableAutoConfiguration` (folded into
  `@SpringBootApplication`) then **reacts to what's on the classpath and what beans you've already
  defined** to configure sensible defaults.
- **Opinionated defaults you can override.** Auto-config beans are almost always guarded by
  `@ConditionalOnMissingBean` (and friends): the moment you declare your own bean of that type, the
  framework **backs off**. You override by *supplying a bean* or *setting a property*, not by editing
  framework code.
- **The application context & component scanning.** `@SpringBootApplication` = `@Configuration` +
  `@EnableAutoConfiguration` + `@ComponentScan`. Scanning starts at the **package of that class** and
  recurses *downward only* — beans in sibling/parent packages are invisible.
- **Externalized config precedence.** The same artifact runs everywhere; config is layered. Later
  sources win: command-line args > `SPRING_APPLICATION_JSON` > OS env vars / system properties >
  `application.properties`/`.yml` (profile-specific files override the plain ones). Details in
  config-actuator.md.
- **Convention over configuration.** Defaults (port 8080, `application.yml` on the classpath, Jackson
  JSON, `/actuator` base path, embedded server) work with zero config; you only declare the
  *deltas*.

## Headline gotchas / common mistakes

- **Component-scan package placement.** Put `@SpringBootApplication` in a **root package above** all
  your code. If a `@Service`/`@Repository` lives outside that subtree it is never registered →
  `NoSuchBeanDefinitionException` or silent nulls. Fix by moving it, or add explicit
  `@ComponentScan(basePackages = …)` / `@Import`.
- **Field injection vs constructor injection.** Prefer **constructor injection** (immutable, testable,
  fails fast on missing deps, no reflection needed in tests). `@Autowired` field injection hides
  dependencies and breaks final fields. A single constructor needs no `@Autowired`.
- **`@Transactional` (and `@Async`/`@Cacheable`) self-invocation.** These work via a proxy. Calling an
  annotated method **from another method in the same bean** (`this.method()`) bypasses the proxy, so
  the advice **does not run**. Call through an injected reference or split the bean. (Persistence
  detail lives in `jpa-hibernate`, but the proxy trap is general.)
- **Mixing servlet + reactive.** `spring-boot-starter-web` and `-webflux` on the same classpath is
  contradictory; Boot defaults to servlet/MVC and your reactive `RouterFunction`s may not behave as
  expected. Pick one stack per app (or force `WebApplicationType` deliberately).
- **Relaxed binding ≠ exact match.** Property keys bind *relaxed*: `my.main-project-name`,
  `my.mainProjectName`, `MY_MAINPROJECTNAME` (env) all bind the same target. Don't assume the env-var
  form must match the dotted form character-for-character — but **do** use the documented uppercase /
  underscore rules for env vars.
- **Auto-config that "won't turn off."** You can't override what you can't see. If a default bean
  persists, it's because your replacement bean has the wrong **type** (the `@ConditionalOnMissingBean`
  matches by type) or your `@Configuration` isn't scanned. Use the `conditions` actuator endpoint /
  `--debug` auto-config report to see why a configuration matched or backed off.

## Live docs protocol

For version-sensitive or uncovered details:

1. **context7 MCP** (best for annotations/properties/starters): library is
   `/spring-projects/spring-boot`. If the context7 tools aren't loaded, load them via ToolSearch
   (`select:mcp__plugin_context7_context7__query-docs`,
   `select:mcp__plugin_context7_context7__resolve-library-id`); if the library id ever fails to
   resolve, call `resolve-library-id` for "Spring Boot" first.
2. **WebFetch `https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/`** — reference docs, properties appendix, and the
   "how-to" guides. For the full property list use the configuration-metadata / application-properties
   appendix.
3. Cross-check surprises against the version-specific reference (the docs are versioned; read the page
   matching the project's detected Boot version).

Say when an answer is **verified-from-docs** vs **from baked-in knowledge**. If the project's Spring
Boot or Java version differs from what you assumed, **adapt and state what differs** (e.g. a property
key was renamed, a starter was split, or a default changed between minor versions).
